TY  - JOUR
AU  - Thomas, Jonathan
AU  - Worrall, Tim
T1  - Self-Enforcing Wage Contracts
PY  - 1988
Y1  - 1988/10/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297404
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 55
IS  - 4
SP  - 541
EP  - 554
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We examine long-term wage contracts between a risk-neutral firm and a risk-averse worker when both can costlessly renege and buy or sell labour at a random spot market wage. A self-enforcing contract is one in which neither party ever has an incentive to renege. In the optimum self-enforcing contract, wages are sticky: they are less variable than spot market wages and positively serially correlated. They are updated by a simple rule: around each spot wage is a time invariant interval, and the contract wage changes each period by the smallest amount necessary to bring it into the current interval.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297404
ER  - 



